04899nam a22007215i 9780691190181DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911901817 a10.1515/97806911901812doi  a(DE-B1597)501810  a(OCoLC)1044836204  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aB105.E9 7aPHI0150002bisacsh04a1282231 aValberg, J. J., eauthor.10aDream, Death, and the Self /cJ. J. Valberg. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tINTRODUCTION. Philosophical Discovery and Philosophical Puzzles -- tPART ONE: Dream -- tTHE MEANING OF THE DREAM HYPOTHESIS -- t1. The Dream Hypothesis and the Argument from Internality -- t2. The Dream Hypothesis: Identity and the First Person -- t3. The Confusion of Standpoint -- t4. The Subject Matter of the Dream Hypothesis -- tDREAM SKEPTICISM -- t5. The Dream Hypothesis and the Skeptical Challenge -- t6. Responding to Dream Skepticism -- tPART TWO: Death -- tTHE MEANING OF DEATH -- t7. I Will Die -- t8. The Subject Matter and "Mineness" of My Death -- tDEATH AND SOLIPSISM -- t9. Solipsism -- t10. Death and the Truth of Solipsism -- t11. The Awfulness and Incomprehensibility of Death -- tPART THREE: The Self -- tPOSSIBILITY AND THE SELF -- t12. Imagination and the Cartesian Self -- t13. Metaphysical Possibility and the Self -- tTHE POSITIONAL CONCEPTION OF THE SELF -- t14. Preliminary Reflections on the Positional Conception of the Self -- t15. The Phenomenology of the Subject Position -- tTHE FIRST PERSON -- t16. The Uses of the First Person -- t17. What Makes First-Person Reference First Personal? -- tTIME AND THE SELF -- t18. Temporalizing the Self -- t19. The Problem of Personal Identity -- t20. Time and the Horizon -- t21. My Past -- t22. My Future -- t23. My Future: The Puzzle of Division -- t24. Conclusion: The Extraphilosophical Puzzles -- tBibliography -- tIndex  a"Might this be a dream?" In this book, distinguished philosopher J. J. Valberg approaches the familiar question about dream and reality by seeking to identify its subject matter: what is it that would be the dream if "this" were a dream? It turns out to be a subject matter that contains the whole of the world, space, and time but which, like consciousness for Sartre, is nothing "in itself." This subject matter, the "personal horizon," lies at the heart of the main topics--the first person, the self, and the self in time--explored at length in the book. The personal horizon is, Valberg contends, the subject matter whose center each of us occupies, and which for each of us ceases with death. This ceasing to be presents itself solipsistically not just as the end of everything "for me" but as the end of everything absolutely. Yet since it is the same for everyone, this cannot be. Death thus confronts us with an impossible fact: something that cannot be but will be. The puzzle about death is one of several extraphilosophical puzzles about the self that Valberg discusses, puzzles that can trouble everyday consciousness without any contribution from philosophy. Nor can philosophy resolve the puzzles. Its task is to get to the bottom of them, and in this respect to understand ourselves--a task philosophy has always set itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aDeath. 0aExperience. 0aSelf-knowledge, Theory of. 0aSolipsism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691190181zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691190181.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ES